Life Expectancy Prediction

CSC532 Final Project

Joseph Le

How do we determine the life quality of a country? Which issues that a country need to improve to provide a better life quality for people? The project will work on a dataset which is collected from most countries in the world. Base on data analysis for the dataset, we could know which predictors could affect life expectancy of a country. Base on the predictors, a country should know how they could make a better life quality. This is the link to the dataset and its variables’ descriptions:

  • Life Expectancy Dataset

  The dataset consists of 22 variables and 2938 observations. There are 2 factors and 20 numeric variables.

1. Data Cleaning

There are spaces in the names of variables so they need to be cleaned.

library(janitor)
life_expectancy <- clean_names(life_expectancy)

 

The name of thinness_1_19_years variable should be changed to thinness_10_19_years since its description showed that the ages are from 10 to 19.

names(life_expectancy)[19] <- "thinness_10_19_years"

 

For the dataset, I’d like to know how education, health care and economic systems affect the life expectancy. Thus, Country and Year variables will be dropped since they are specific identifiers and not used in the purpose of predicting the life expectancy.

life_expectancy <- life_expectancy[-c(1,2)]

 

There are some missing values in the outcome variable life_expectancy so they need to be removed.

life_expectancy <-  life_expectancy[!is.na(life_expectancy$life_expectancy),]

3. Creating Predictive Models

Now we can start to working on machine learning models to predict life expectancy of a country based on the features. There are three categories of models including Regularized Linear Regression, Tree-based Ensemble, and Neural Networks with drop out layers.

Creating Regularized Linear Regression Models

These models consist of Lasso, Ridge, and Elastic net. 10 fold cross validation is used for all the models. RMSE of each model is computed and later used for comparisons between machine learning models.

library(caret)
index <- createDataPartition(life_expectancy_imp_app$life_expectancy, p = 0.90, list = FALSE, times=1)
life_expectancy_train <- life_expectancy_imp_app[index,]
life_expectancy_test <- life_expectancy_imp_app[-index,]

set.seed(1)
lasso <- train(
  life_expectancy ~., data = life_expectancy_train, method = "glmnet",
  trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10),
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(alpha = 1, lambda = 10^seq(-3, 3, length = 100)))
coef(lasso$finalModel, lasso$bestTune$lambda)
predictions <- predict(lasso,life_expectancy_test)
RMSE(predictions, life_expectancy_test$life_expectancy)

set.seed(1)
ridge <- train(
  life_expectancy ~., data = life_expectancy_train, method = "glmnet",
  trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10),
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(alpha = 0, lambda = 10^seq(-3, 3, length = 100)))
predictions <- predict(ridge,life_expectancy_test)
RMSE(predictions, life_expectancy_test$life_expectancy)

set.seed(1)
enet <- train(
  life_expectancy ~., data = life_expectancy_train, method = "glmnet",
  trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10),
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(alpha =seq(0,1, length=10), lambda = 10^seq(-3, 3, length = 100)))
predictions <- predict(enet,life_expectancy_test)
RMSE(predictions, life_expectancy_test$life_expectancy)

 

Creating Tree-Ensemble Models

The models consist of Random Forest model and Gradient Boosted Tree model. In the Caret package, “rf” method is used to train a random forest model on the traning data to predict life_expectancy. “gbm” method is used to train Gradient Boosted Tree model. In similar to Regularized Linear Regression Models, 10 fold cross validation is used for all the models. RMSEs are also computed.

set.seed(1)
library(randomForest)
rf <- randomForest(life_expectancy ~ ., data = life_expectancy_train, importance=T)
randomForest(formula=life_expectancy ~ ., data = life_expectancy_train)

Creating a Neural Network Model

Neural Network model with drop out layres is used to predict life expectancy. The model does not accept categorical variables so the variables must be converted to numeric variables. After all processes of analyzing the dataset, there is only one categorical variable left which is status. It has two levels including “Developed” and “Developing” so as.numeric is used to convert the factor variable to numeric variable.

life_expectancy_train$status <- as.numeric(ifelse(life_expectancy_train$status=="Developed", 0, 1))
life_expectancy_test$status <- as.numeric(ifelse(life_expectancy_test$status=="Developed", 0, 1))

 

The traning data is divided into two portions: a training set with 90 percent of the examples and a validation set with 10 percent.

set.seed(1)
index <- createDataPartition(life_expectancy_train$life_expectancy, p = 0.90, list = FALSE, times=1)  

life_expectancy_partial_train <- life_expectancy_train[index,]
life_expectancy_val <- life_expectancy_train[-index,]

train_data <- life_expectancy_partial_train[,-20]
train_labels <- life_expectancy_partial_train[,20]
test_data <- life_expectancy_test[,-20]
test_labels <- life_expectancy_test[,20]
val_data <- life_expectancy_val[,-20]
val_labels <- life_expectancy_val[,20]

 

The data should always be normalized before using it for neural networks. The scale function is used for z-score normalization. Training data would be scaled and the mean and std are also computed. The column means and standard deviations are used to scale test data and validation data.

life_expectancy_train_scale = scale(train_data[,-1])
col_means_train <- attr(life_expectancy_train_scale, "scaled:center")
col_stddevs_train <- attr(life_expectancy_train_scale, "scaled:scale")
life_expectancy_test_scale <- scale(test_data[,-1], center = col_means_train, scale = col_stddevs_train)
life_expectancy_val_scale <- scale(val_data[,-1], center = col_means_train, scale = col_stddevs_train)

train_data <- cbind(life_expectancy_train_scale, train_data[,1])
test_data <- cbind(life_expectancy_test_scale, test_data[,1]) 
val_data <- cbind(life_expectancy_val_scale, val_data[,1])

 

Tuning Hyper-parameters

The ANNs will need to tune a large number of hyper-parameters including the number of hidden layers, the number of drop out layers, activation functions of hidden layers, and others. A set of flags is created to run the model. The life_expectancy.R file is created for tuning_run function.

library(keras)
library(tfruns)
package 㤼㸱tfruns㤼㸲 was built under R version 3.6.3
library(rlang)
package 㤼㸱rlang㤼㸲 was built under R version 3.6.3
runs <- tuning_run("life_expectancy.R", 
                  flags = list(
                  nodes_1 = c(30, 50, 70),
                  nodes_2 = c(10, 20, 30),
                  dropout_1 = c(0.3,0.4),
                  dropout_2 = c(0.2, 0.3),
                  learning_rate = c(0.01, 0.05, 0.001, 0.0001),                 
                  batch_size=c(50,75,100,150),
                  epochs=c(10,20,30),
                  activation_1=c("relu","sigmoid","tanh"),
                  activation_2=c("relu","sigmoid","tanh")
                   ),
                   sample = 0.001
)

After tuned hyper-parameters, the best validation performance is collected. The best run had 50 neurons in the first hidden layer and 20 neurons in the second hidden layer with 0.4 in first dropout layer and 0.2 in second dropout layer. It had tanh activation in first hidden layer and sigmoid activation in second hidden layer and was trained for 20 epochs with learing_rate = 0.01, batch_size = 50. However, it is overfit as validation loss is lower than training loss.

model =keras_model_sequential() 
model %>%
  layer_dense(units = 50, activation = "tanh", input_shape = c(19)) %>%
  layer_dropout(rate = 0.4) %>%
  layer_dense(units = 20, activation = "sigmoid") %>%
  layer_dropout(rate = 0.2) %>%
  layer_dense(units = 1)

model %>% compile(
  optimizer = optimizer_sgd(lr=0.01), 
  loss = "mse")

ann_history <- model %>% fit(
  as.matrix(train_data_all), 
  train_labels_all, 
  epochs = 20, 
  batch_size= 50, 
  validation_data=list(as.matrix(test_data), test_labels))

Results

As the results of RSMEs, we could see that errors of the machine learning models are low. This meant that the machine learning models performed good in predicting the life expectancy. Random Forest seemed to be the best model since its rmse is lowest compared to others models.
